06188nam a22011895i 9781400888030DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20172017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008880307 a10.1515/97814008880302doi  a(DE-B1597)490451  a(OCoLC)995163694  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0090002bisacsh04a297.2/612231 aEl Shakry, Omnia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Arabic Freud :bPsychoanalysis and Islam in Modern Egypt /cOmnia El Shakry. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration and Translation -- tIntroduction. Psychoanalysis and Islam -- tPART I. THE UNCONSCIOUS AND THE MODERN SUBJECT -- t1. Psychoanalysis and the Psyche -- t2. The Self and the Soul -- tPART II. SPACES OF INTERIORITY -- t3. The Psychosexual Subject -- t4. Psychoanalysis before the Law -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first in-depth look at how postwar thinkers in Egypt mapped the intersections between Islamic discourses and psychoanalytic thoughtIn 1945, psychologist Yusuf Murad introduced an Arabic term borrowed from the medieval Sufi philosopher and mystic Ibn 'Arabi-al-la-shu'ur-as a translation for Sigmund Freud's concept of the unconscious. By the late 1950s, Freud's Interpretation of Dreams had been translated into Arabic for an eager Egyptian public. In The Arabic Freud, Omnia El Shakry challenges the notion of a strict divide between psychoanalysis and Islam by tracing how postwar thinkers in Egypt blended psychoanalytic theories with concepts from classical Islamic thought in a creative encounter of ethical engagement.Drawing on scholarly writings as well as popular literature on self-healing, El Shakry provides the first in-depth examination of psychoanalysis in Egypt and reveals how a new science of psychology-or "science of the soul," as it came to be called-was inextricably linked to Islam and mysticism. She explores how Freudian ideas of the unconscious were crucial to the formation of modern discourses of subjectivity in areas as diverse as psychology, Islamic philosophy, and the law. Founding figures of Egyptian psychoanalysis, she shows, debated the temporality of the psyche, mystical states, the sexual drive, and the Oedipus complex, while offering startling insights into the nature of psychic life, ethics, and eros.This provocative and insightful book invites us to rethink the relationship between psychoanalysis and religion in the modern era. Mapping the points of intersection between Islamic discourses and psychoanalytic thought, it illustrates how the Arabic Freud, like psychoanalysis itself, was elaborated across the space of human difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aIslam and psychoanalysis. 0aPsychoanalysis and religion. 0aPsychoanalysiszEgyptxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychotherapyxReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh  aAbu al-Wafa al-Ghunaymi al-Taftazani.  aArabic.  aEgypt.  aEgyptian legal system.  aIslam.  aIslamic discourses.  aIslamic philosophy.  aIslamic tradition.  aJulia Kristeva.  aMajallat ʿIlm al-Nafs.  aMuhammad Fathi.  aMuhammad Mustafa Hilmi.  aSigmund Freud.  aSufism.  aYusuf Murad.  aclassical Islam.  acrime.  acriminal.  adesire.  adivine discourse.  adivine transcendence.  aethical encounters.  aethical engagement.  aethics.  aforensic practices.  agender.  ahuman difference.  alaw.  alegal regim